Meta Analysis

This simulation study tests:

  1. How publication bias affects ability to detect moderators in meta-analysis

  2. Whether adjustments for publication bias may improve or impair detection of moderators, given publication bias.

Data are simulated according to two scenarios:

• Medium effects: Studies have true effects of 0, 0.3, or 0.6

• Small effects: Studies have true effects of 0, 0.2, or 0.4

• Data are then subjected to publication bias and QRPs

• No bias: All study results are reported

• Biased: Only 20% of of nonsignificant results are published. 50% of studies involve aggressive p-hacking, 40% use moderate p-hacking.

• Number of studies per group is fixed to k = 20

• Studies have sample size of minimum 20/cell, maximum 200/cell, average 50/cell.

Analysis

Naïve analysis: Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect without adjustment for publication bias

WLS-MRA (single slope): Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect after PET adjustment for publication bias. PET slope is fixed across groups.

WLS-MRA (variable slope): Meta-analysis tests the moderator effect after PET adjustment for publication bias. PET slope may vary across groups. Results are presented in terms of bias, root mean squared error, and Type I/II error.

Results

Medium effects

Group Means: 0, 0.3, 0.6

Publication bias causes overestimation of δ = 0 and underestimation of mods. This underestimation causes increased Type II error rates for moderators. PET-RMA does not quite undo this bias and can have poor power and efficiency.

Small Effects

Group means: 0, 0.2, 0.4

When effects are smaller, the loss of power is more pronounced. Again, PET-RMA does not fix the biases and can inflict further loss of efficiency.

Significance Rates

No publication bias, no QRPs

Type I error rate. Under the null, all methods had appropriate Type I error rates, with the exception of p-curve and 3PSM, which were a bit too conservative. P-curve and p-uniform often failed to provide an estimate due to the scarcity of statistically significant results.

The addition of heterogeneity lead to a modest increase in Type I error rates for random-effects meta-analysis, trim-and-fill, WAAP-WLS, and PET-PEESE, as well as a considerable increase in Type I error rates for p-curve and p-uniform. Heterogeneity did not increase Type I error rates for 3PSM, which remained excessively conservative.

Power. Random-effects meta-analysis offered the best power of all methods, followed closely by trim-and-fill, 3PSM, p-curve, and WAAP-WLS. Power was poorer for p-uniform and PET-PEESE. Despite this, all methods had 100% by k = 60.

The addition of heterogeneity slightly increased the power of p-curve and p-uniform and slightly reduced the power of trim-and-fill, 3PSM, and WAAP-WLS. Heterogeneity substantially reduced PET-PEESE’s power in small samples (44% at k = 10). Despite this, all methods had >95% power at k = 60.

ME. All methods were generally unbiased. Trim-and-fill showed a slight downward bias in general (-0.01), and PET-PEESE showed a slightly stronger downward bias, particularly when the null was false. PET-PEESE’s downward bias was mitigated by larger k, however. P-curve and p-uniform both exhibited upward bias under the null, but were unbiased when the null was false. P-uniform’s upward bias was stronger than that of p-curve.

Heterogeneity had little effect on the bias of random effects, WAAP-WLS, and 3PSM. It added upward bias to p-curve and p-uniform and downward bias to trim-and-fill and PET-PEESE.

RMSE. Random-effects meta-analysis provided the most efficient results and smallest RMSE. RMSE was slightly greater for WAAP-WLS, trim-and-fill, and 3PSM. RMSE was noticeably poorer for PET-PEESE, p-curve, and p-uniform. Consistent with the situations in which these methods demonstrate bias, RMSE was particularly poorer for p-curve and p-uniform when the null was true and poorer for PET-PEESE when the null was false.

Heterogeneity only slightly increased the RMSE of random effects, trim-and-fill, WAAP-WLS, and 3PSM. Heterogeneity lead to a more noticeable increase in the RMSE of p-curve, p-uniform, and PET-PEESE.

95% CI coverage. Coverage rates of random-effects meta analysis were ideal at 95%. WAAP-WLS, PET-PEESE, p-uniform, and 3PSM had roughly correct coverage rates (+/- 2%). Trim-and-fill suffered from some when k was large.

Heterogeneity caused slightly poorer coverage for all methods. For random-effects meta-analysis and 3PSM, greater k helped to restore coverage rates. For trim-and-fill, p-uniform, and PET-PEESE, greater k exacerbated the undercoverage. WAAP-WLS had only slight undercoverage regardless of k.

Strong publication bias, no QRPs

Type I error rates. Random-effects meta-analysis suffered from false positive rates of 98% and higher. Trim-and-fill had slightly lower, but still unacceptable Type I error rates in excess of 90%. WAAP-WLS had better Type I error rates that were still quite poor (>80%); unlike these other methods, Type I error rates decreased with increasing k. 3PSM had lower Type I error rates (37%) at k = 10, but these errors increased with increasing k. P-curve, p-uniform, and PET-PEESE had approximately conservative Type I error rates ranging from 3-9%.

The addition of heterogeneity slightly reduced the Type I error rate for random-effects, trim-and-fill, and WAAP-WLS, but these Type I error rates remained unacceptably high (>60%). Heterogeneity also substantially increased the Type I error rates of p-curve and p-uniform, leading to error rates of >35% at k = 10 and >90% at k = 60. Heterogeneity also increased the Type I error rate of PET-PEESE and 3PSM.

[Isn’t this odd that 3PSM has elevated Type I error rates? Is it because of the imputation of prob = .01 when no nonsig results? Or our exclusion of certain runs? Or, aha, the misspecification of the selection model!]

Power. Random-effects meta-analysis and trim-and-fill had approximately 100% power at all levels of k. WAAP-WLS and 3PSM had only slightly poorer power, about 95% at k = 10 and about 100% at k = 60. P-curve and p-uniform also had good (>90%) power even at small k. PET-PEESE had substantially poorer power with small samples (53% at k = 10), but its power approached 100% with larger k.

Heterogeneity did not harm the power of random effects, trim-and-fill, or WAAP-WLS. It increased the power of p-curve and p-uniform. Heterogeneity slightly reduced the power of 3PSM, but its power remained good (>90%).

ME. Under the null, many methods were badly biased upwards. Random effects meta-analysis estimated the null effect as about 0.30. WAAP-WLS and trim-and-fill did not substantially reduce this bias, both estimating the effect as about 0.25. p-curve, p-uniform, and 3PSM overestimated null results, but less so than other methods. This tendency was stronger for p-uniform than for p-curve, and the bias decreased with increasing k. PET-PEESE was unbiased.

When the null was false, random effects still slightly overestimated the true effect. Trim-and-fill and WAAP-WLS both reduced this slight bias. P-curve, p-uniform, and 3PSM were unbiased in estimating the true effect. PET-PEESE tended to underestimate the true effect, although this tendency was ameliorated with increasing k.

Adding heterogeneity to a true effect of zero tended to exacerbate bias. Random-effects meta-analysis, trim-and-fill, WAAP-WLS, and PET-PEESE all demonstrated slight upward bias under heterogeneity. p-curve and p-uniform demonstrated substantial upward bias under heterogeneity; this tendency was

stronger for p-curve than for p-uniform, and increasing k did not help. In contrast, 3PSM did not demonstrate greater bias under heterogeneity.

Adding heterogeneity to a true nonzero effect also tended to move estimates upwards. This caused slightly greater upward bias in random effects, trim and fill, and WAAP-WLS; slightly reduced downward bias in PET-PEESE; and created upward bias in p-curve and p-uniform. 3PSM remained unbiased.

RMSE. Given the null, RMSE was considerably elevated for random effects, and all adjustments lead to some improvement in RMSE. WAAP-WLS and trim and fill lead to modest improvements, and p-uniform, PET-PEESE, 3PSM, and p-curve lead to successively greater improvements. The difference in benefits between TF and WAAP-WLS vs 3PSM, p-curve, p-uniform, and PET-PEESE was particularly pronounced at higher k.

Given a true effect, RMSE was not too bad for random effects meta-analysis. Given high k, all methods provided some benefit to RMSE, with the exception of PET-PEESE, which was comparable to random effects meta-analysis. Given small k, only some methods slightly reduced RMSE: p-uniform, 3PSM, WAAP-WLS, and TF. P-curve slightly increased RMSE, and PET-PEESE dramatically increased it. [Perhaps PET-PEESE is a bad idea at k = 10.]

Given the null and heterogeneity, RMSE increased modestly all around, and all methods provided some benefit relative to unadjusted random-effects. The greatest improvement was provided by 3PSM.

Given a true effect and heterogeneity, RMSE increased moderately. All methods provided some benefit relative to unadjusted random-effects, with the exception of PET-PEESE when k was small. 3PSM and TF provided the greatest improvement in RMSE.

95% CI coverage. Given the null, because of the considerable publication bias, 95% CI coverage was very poor without adjustment. All methods lead to some improvement in coverage. Benefits of TF were slight. Benefits of WAAP-WLS increased with k, but coverage still did not improve beyond 20%. Benefits of 3PSM, on the other hand, decreased with k, yielding 62% coverage at k = 10 but 5% coverage at k = 60. p-uniform and PET-PEESE were the only methods to yield coverage rates better than 90% and not exceeding 96%.

Given a true effect, CI coverage was much better. However, as k increased, coverage fell, presumably due to some combination of bias and insufficient CI width. 3PSM and p-uniform gave appropriate coverage frequencies. WAAP-WLS and TF demonstrated undercoverage, and PET-PEESE demonstrated undercoverage that grew worse with increasing k.

Given the null and heterogeneity, random effects CI coverage was slightly better but still very poor. All adjustments slightly improved CI coverage, with the greatest benefits observed from 3PSM and PET-PEESE. Even these improvements were suboptimal, reaching coverage rates no greater than 80%, and coverage grew worse with greater k.
